<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Symbol;">&middot;</span><span style="">&nbsp; </span>Day 28 - Favourite movie from your favourite director</p>  <br />This is <em>impossible</em>! I've been thinking over and over this, and I can't come to a concluision. My favourite director, that's easy, clearly it's <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0942367/">Edgar Wright.</a><br /><br /><a href="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000ctzb3/"><img border="0" alt="" style="width: 244px; height: 184px;" src="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000ctzb3/s320x240" /></a> <br /><br />But my favourite of his films? I can't pick.&nbsp; I love them all, really I do, and I'm not sure I&nbsp;could pick. So, I'm going to cheat. And talk about them all.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0365748/">Shaun of the Dead (2004)</a><br /><br /><a href="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cw9xc/"><img border="0" src="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cw9xc/s320x240" style="width: 191px; height: 143px;" alt="" /></a><br />I'm trying to remember if I'd seen Spaced before this came out... I think not, as I was just 15 when it did. So this was my first introduction to the genius of Edgar Wright. It's just so undeniably British. So wonderfully home grown. How can I not love it?<br /><br /><a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0425112/">Hot Fuzz (2007)</a><br /><br /><a href="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cx117/"><img border="0" src="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cx117/s320x240" style="width: 110px; height: 163px;" alt="" /></a><br /><br />I find the characters slightly more likeable than in Shaun, and more shit blows up. But I still can't pick it above SOTD. Genius. Just genius in a slightly different way. It's less.... initmate. The whole scope of this film is bigger.  <br /><br /><a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0446029/">Scot Pilgrim Vs The World (2010)</a><br /><br /><a href="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cyb0a/"><img border="0" src="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000cyb0a/s320x240" style="width: 114px; height: 169px;" alt="" /></a><br />Not one of the Blood and Ice Cream Trilogy, on the other hand, fantastic. I can kind of see what Simon Pegg means when he says it's the closest thing to a third series of Spaced that we're going to get. <br /><br />I know I've been rather terse talking about these films, but, well, I hardly need to explain the plots to anyone. And I think the reasons why I like them are obvious. They are funny, intelligent, well written, nicely paced, have brilliant plots and have that inimitable Edgar Wright style that is unforgettable. Genius and 5 star through and through. And you can't make me play favourites!

So, yeah, watching Die Hard last night made me feel better. As did eating chocolate and talking to my mum. And if I'm honest probably the latter. However, I also fell dead asleep whilst watching in (thank goodness I've got into the habit of setting the sleep timer on my tv) So there was no post yesterday. <br />Today was uneventful. All that happened was I&nbsp;got soaked on my way home from work. Properly drenched. Wouldn't have minded so much except I was 10 minutes away from home which meant if I hadn't stopped by the station on my way home to pick up some train tickets, I'd have been home before it started. And I phoned up to grumble at the broadband people. To get anything done in this country, you have to complain till you're blue in the nose. Maybe I'll have internet by the end of next week. You never know.<br /><br />So, memewards:<br /><br /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
