<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal"><strong><span style="font-family: Symbol;">&middot;</span><span style="">&nbsp; </span>Day 24 - That one awesome movie idea that still hasn&rsquo;t been done yet</strong><br /><br />Hmmm... well I'd quite like them to properly make The Dark Is Rising Sequence into a series of films. They would make fantastic family films in the vein of the Narnia series. But I guess that the books aren't well known enough and maybe a little too British to really make it to a wider audience. And considering the utter hatchet job they made of The Dark Is Rising (the second book in the series for a start, and these stories really need to be told in order) maybe they should just stary away. I love these books too much to see them butchered.<br />So I think<br /><br /><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_Mis%C3%A9rables_%28musical%29">A film of the musical of the book of Les Miserables.</a><br /><br /><a href="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000ch0a7/"><img width="320" height="212" border="0" alt="" src="http://pics.livejournal.com/niblick_iii/pic/000ch0a7/s320x240" /></a><br />(John Owen-Jones as Jean Valjean. Because.)<br /><br />It's a great show. It's in it's 25th year currently, and still playing to packed houses. Hell, it's popular enough to withstand <em>two concurrent West End productions</em>.(The original and the 25th Anniversary Tour which is finishing it's run in, I believe, the Barbican)<br />Yes, the show is long, and no, I'm not sure there is all that much you could cut, but I would gladly sit through a film that long. They would have to be careful not to stunt cast too much and make sure they cast people who can actually sing and act, but I think they could do it. I'm not going to dream cast it here, because we'd be here all night and I would be casting people most of you will never have hear of or care about.<br />The show is just so spectacular, so moving, so brilliant that I think it would work. Sure, it would make everyone cry, but (judging by my reaction) they'd just want to march back in and see it again. There have been <a href="http://www.imdb.com/find?s=all&amp;q=les+miserables">numerous attempts</a> to adapt Victor Hugo's classic novel (and yes, before you ask, I have read the unabridged novel. More than once. And I&nbsp;think it's fantastic) with varying degrees of success. I think though, that the musical is the closest you can come the feeling of the 1200 page book. The music can convey more of the emotion and sentiment that gets lost in the necessary editing than mere words could do. <br />So anyway. That's my pick. A film of Les Miserables. With singing.</p>  </meta></meta></meta></meta></meta></meta></meta></meta>
